LAGOS  – The Lagos State Government has urged residents of Egbe-Idimu and Ayobo-Ipaja Local Council Development Areas (LCDAs)to facilitate hitch-free construction of a network of roads in the two localities. Dr. Idris Salako, the Commissioner for Physical Planning and Urban Development, said at the Stakeholders meeting in Alausa that the road network was crucial to link the two contiguous council areas through the construction of a 250m deck-on-pile bridge, in addition to 1.57km pavement road network. Salako, who spoke through the Director Technical Services, Tpl. Bola Aliu,pointed out, that the project would bring about enhanced social and economic activities in Egbe-Idimu and Ayobo-Ipaja Local Council Development Areas. He said that in line with the THEMES Agenda, the Mr. Babajide Sanwo-Olu led administration was accelerating the development of the State across many fronts, particularly road and transport infrastructure development among others. His words: “ In deed, efforts of the State Government at enhancing connectivity within the Alimosho axis, as in other parts of the State, is in fulfilment of the electoral promise to improve living standards and make life more abundant and meaningful for residents of the State, majorly residing in this acclaimed population hub of Lagos State”, The Commissioner stated that to ensure the successful take-off of public projects, the Ministry of Physical Planning and Urban Development was saddled with the mandate of ensuring that project sites were delivered unencumbered to contractors through the establishment of the Right of Way, which is usually preceded by adequate notices through newspaper and dialogue meetings amongst others.